<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Market rejects Gas tale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The stock market was alarmed yesterday at a story in the weekend press that
British Gas may be forced into cutting its dividend by the end of the year,
because of the impact of regulatory pressures on its profits. Gas is
scheduled to report first-quarter results on Thursday.
The shares were by far the worst performer in the FT-SE 100 Index, falling 9
1/2 to 284 1/2 p ex-dividend, and were the most heavily traded with more
than 18m changing hands.
Gas shares have moved erratically in recent weeks, plunging to 280p on April
28 following a profits warning, and racing up to more than 300p last week as
the market gave a positive reaction to the Department of Trade/Ofgas report
on competition and pricing in UK domestic gas supply.
Many analysts were sceptical of the dividend threat story. 'Gas declined to
discuss the dividend when it made its profits warning in April, and a
dividend cut seems most unlikely this year,' said one. Another said that Gas
will pay maintained dividends in the near term, although its ability to do
so post-1996 depends on progress on cost-cutting. 'There is a long term risk
to Gas's dividend but not so in the short term,' he added.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4923 Gas Transmission and Distribution.
</IN>
