<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / International Company News: Sony Music suffers decline in
sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sony Music Entertainment, the 71 per cent-owned entertainment subsidiary of
the Sony electronics group, yesterday unveiled a fall in profits and its
first annual sales decline for nine years.
Pre-tax profits fell 11.7 per cent to Y19.84bn (Dollars 189.4m) on sales
down 1.2 per cent to Y99.6bn. This was a result of lack of hits by Japanese
musicians, said Mr Kazutoshi Shiraishi, Sony Music Entertainment's managing
director.
The poor performance of domestic music was only partially offset by
increased sales of discs by Billy Joel, experiencing a revival in Japan, and
other foreign stars.
Net profits rose 0.6 per cent to Y12.01bn, due to a temporary drop in
corporate tax payments, but will shrink again to an expected Y9.7bn this
year as the tax bill rises, said Mr Shiraishi. He expects a revival in sales
of Japanese music discs, but not in foreign discs or video-cassettes. On
these grounds, he forecast pre-tax profits to fall this year to Y18.5bn, on
sales of Y99.3bn.
The annual divided has been increased to Y25 per share from Y22.5. Earnings
per share fell from Y133.36 to Y116.62 last year, due to dilution caused by
a share issue.
</TEXT>
