<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Part-time move for AA insurance staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AA Insurance Services, one of the UK's biggest motor and home insurance
retailers, is to switch many of its 5,100 staff to more flexible labour
contracts in response to the growth of telephone insurance companies such as
Direct Line.
This will mean further part-time working for the mainly female labour force
as the company seeks to reduce costs and increase the efficiency and
flexibility of its network of 250 shops.
More details will come next month when the company, which is in talks with
unions about the changes, announces an overhaul of its operations.
Like other chains of insurance shops, the AA has lost business over the past
three years to Direct Line and other 'direct writers', insurers which sell
by telephone directly to the public, bypassing the industry's traditional
middlemen.
Recent price competition in motor insurance has also put extra pressure on
margins. Shops which typically obtain a commission from insurers of between
10 and 15 per cent on business sold have seen their income squeezed by
recent falls in premium rates.
'There is a fundamental change in the amount of margin available as a reward
for distributing insurance products,' said Mr Mark Wood, who became AA
Insurance Services managing director earlier this year.
The AA expects the amount of commissions on motor insurance available to the
country's brokers and intermediaries to fall from Pounds 700m in 1992 to
Pounds 435m in 1995.
Mr Wood said the competitive pressures faced by chains of insurance shops
from the 'direct writers' were similar to those faced by supermarkets from
discount warehouses.
The number of AA Insurance part-time staff has increased from 420 in 1988 to
more than 1,400 and seems likely to rise further as greater flexibility is
introduced to shop opening hours, with evening and Saturday afternoon
opening.
'Frequently insurance brokers tend to say: 'Let's open our offices when
everyone is at work'. We need to turn that on its head,' said Mr Wood.
'The industry is very confused about the retailing proposition. There is a
traditional view of us being a service like an accountant or a solicitor.'
The AA recognised that more consumers were prepared to buy insurance over
the telephone, but Mr Wood insisted that the group's network of shops made
it ideally placed to offer follow-up on claims and alterations to policies
which customers frequently preferred to handle on a face-to-face basis.
Recent moves by companies such as Burton and Sock Shop indicate a growing
trend towards part-time employment in retailing.
</TEXT>
