<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There seems to be no let up in the passion for elephant-on-the-floor
documentaries: those programmes where an entire television crew with camera
and sound gear creeps around like an elephant in gym shoes while the local
inhabitants go about their business, studiously pretending to be unaware of
the disruption. 20 Miles From Piccadilly Circus is the first in a six part
series about life in Eynsford, Kent. This week the effort is on to win the
'Britain In Bloom' competition (7.30 ITV). In Assignment Brian Barron
reports on Australia's new law of 'Native Title' which enables aborigines to
reclaim ancestral lands. It seems to have raised the same sort of problem as
the idea of returning museum pieces to the original owners: where do you
stop? (7.45 BBC2). Frederic Raphael pursues Jeremy Bentham's argument in
Without Walls, that 'All talk of rights is nonsense on stilts'. He says that
today's pursuit of special rights for women, homosexuals and racial
minorities encourages people to see themselves as victims and everyone else
as enemies (9.00 C4).
</TEXT>
