<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Pension schemes criticise industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A third of pension schemes believe the industry does not communicate
effectively with its members, says a survey released yesterday.
A third also believe that pension-scheme members understand little of the
financial information presented to them, the survey commissioned by
accountants Clark Whitehill indicates. The analysis was based on a sample of
196 schemes with a total of 1.6m members. Nearly two-thirds of schemes rely
on the small amount of information contained in summary financial statements
sent to members.
Clark Whitehill called for regulation of the contents and distribution of
summary reports for members and said that reports should require a separate
auditor's and actuary's report. It said its findings underlined concerns
raised by the Goode committee on pension fund reform about the level of
'gobbledegook' in pension scheme literature.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
