<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / DTI may extend copyright to TV programme formats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday said it was considering
whether copyright protection should be extended to programme formats.
A programme format is seen as comprising the 'common unifying features' of a
game show or situation comedy.
In 1989 the Privy Council decided that the unifying features of the talent
show Opportunity Knocks, which had been copied by the New Zealand
Broadcasting Corporation, did not constitute a work protected by copyright
law.
Ministers are now considering whether further protection is needed
especially as the government has been trying to find ways to encourage
Britain's broadcasters to export more programmes.
The DTI has issued a consultation paper and is seeking comment by June 24.
'For example, concern has been expressed that protecting formats could
result in simple programming ideas being monopolised with consequent
restrictions on programming freedom,' the department said.
At present broadcasters often either pay for or acknowledge another's
format, but only on an informal basis.
CBS, the US network, was angered last year when the BBC launched its 999
series featuring stories of survival in dangerous circumstances. CBS
believed it had much in common with its programme Rescue 911.
</TEXT>
