<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Employers oppose rule change for pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior directors of several large companies including Imperial Chemical
Industries and Unilever told MPs at an unpublicised meeting that they
opposed a central recommendation of the Goode committee on pensions
regulation, it emerged last night. The Goode proposals were drawn up in the
wake of the Maxwell scandal.
Directors of the companies, which also included the J. Sainsbury and Tesco
retail chains, were invited to a meeting by members of the Conservative
majority on the Commons social security committee.
The directors said they rejected Goode's proposals for legislation ensuring
that at least a third of trustees are appointed by scheme members. That was
put forward by Goode because employee contributions make up a third of most
schemes' assets.
The Tory majority on the committee asked the businessmen to give evidence at
a special meeting. It was called last week after the Conservatives rejected
the first draft of the committee's report. They opposed it for advocating
too many new rules. The Tories are determined that the government should
avoid over-regulation.
The handling of the issue, including the involvement of some of the biggest
employers in Britain, has enraged some Labour members of the committee. They
are considering publishing a minority report in favour of further regulation
to prevent the possibility of further pension scandals.
Ministers fear that if the Goode proposal were implemented it might
seriously undermine occupational pensions because managements might question
the value of such schemes if they did not have absolute control of the
trustees.
They are 'delighted' that the company chiefs gave evidence to the committee
underlining their view that it would be a mistake to over-regulate.
The government, which is to publish its white paper later this year, favours
a code of 'best practice', which would leave the composition of the board of
trustees to the management, as is now the case.
While some of the companies which appeared before the committee already
allow scheme members to appoint more than a third of trustees, they oppose a
change in the law which would force them to comply with the measure.
One of the companies said: 'There is now so much regulation that no pension
fund can be sure that they are keeping up with the latest requirement.'
According to a Whitehall official, the message from employers to ministers
is: 'Resist the temptation to over-regulate.'
Schemes critical, Page 12
</TEXT>
