<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Business chief to head probe of Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury yesterday announced that a leading industrialist will supervise
a planned internal review of its senior management structure and disclosed
details of the fundamental review of its spending and running costs that was
announced with the November 1993 Budget.
Sir Colin Southgate, chairman of Thorn EMI and PowerGen and a member of the
Court of the Bank of England, will supervise a 'senior open structure
review' looking into possible changes to the way the Treasury deploys senior
staff.
As part of the review of running costs, Sir Colin will supervise an
examination by Treasury staff of how work in their directorates should be
developed and organised.
Detailed work on the organisation of directorates and the allocation of
resources will be carried out by a team headed by Mr Jeremy Heywood, who was
principal private secretary to Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr
Norman Lamont, his predecessor.
This part of the review, which will also look at the Treasury's relations
with other organisations and how to contain spending growth, will be
completed in the autumn. The Treasury review of its programme expenditure,
such as payments to the Bank of England and Royal Mint, will be co-ordinated
by Mr Kit Chivers. The results will influence the Treasury's internal
budgeting for 1995-96.
</TEXT>
