<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Plan for old power stations faces rejection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Large electricity users are to tell the government that the idea that they
might buy spare generating capacity to help keep their costs down is
unlikely to be practicable.
They say the costs of improving older power stations to meet new laws on
sulphur dioxide emissions would be prohibitive. Their electricity would
eventually cost more than they pay now from the 'pool' run by the
generators.
Even to buy a plant and run it unimproved until the new laws come into
effect in the year 2001 would involve higher costs than the pool, as they
would be liable for redundancy payments, decommissioning, demolition and
environmental clean-ups, possibly costing more than Pounds 100m a plant.
A delegation of big users, Tory and Labour MPs, and council leaders is
arranging to see Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, in the next few weeks.
The move will dash government hopes that selling power stations to big users
could solve their pool-prices problem.
Under the pool system, the price of electricity varies every half-hour and
is fixed at the marginal cost of production of the last available plant
brought on stream to fill national demand. Winter tea-times should be the
costliest periods. In practice, prices have varied according to what plant
is 'available'.
Imperial Chemical Industries has warned it might pull out of
energy-intensive chlorine production - threatening more than 7,000 jobs - if
the issue was not resolved.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the industry regulator, last year persuaded
the generators to peg pool prices to an annual average of 2.4p per kWh and
obtained a commitment from them to offer spare generating capacity for sale.
ICI, Pilkington and British Steel are among several companies that have
formed a loose consortium to consider buying the 2,000MW Fiddlers Ferry
power station at Widnes, only a few miles from ICI's chlorine plant at
Runcorn, Cheshire, and Pilkington's glass factories at St Helens,
Merseyside. The electricity generators paid the government Pounds 100,000
for each MW of generating capacity on privatisation, so Fiddlers Ferry would
have cost PowerGen about Pounds 200m. The asking price is therefore likely
to be in the Pounds 100m to Pounds 150m range.
But the plant is an obsolete coal-fired station and operates only because
the government's pollution inspectorate tolerates its emissions of sulphur
dioxide. Some members of the consortium say there is a risk it could be shut
down at any time.
Power Generation Equipment, separate section
</TEXT>
