<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Large job growth forecast for City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Central London is likely to see a growth in total office employment of
between 50,000 and 65,000 jobs by the year 2000, according to a report
published yesterday.
The growth in office employment could generate demand for nearly 10m sq ft
of extra office space, according to a report by the chartered surveyors St
Quintin.
The employment growth is likely to be less important in generating demand
for offices however, than the need for City occupiers to change and upgrade
their accommodation. A quarter of City tenants are housed in unrefurbished
buildings built before 1970.
An anticipated growth in the amount of floorspace occupied by each worker is
also expected to increase demand by up to 4.5m sq ft.
The report says the chance of another explosion in the financial and
business services sectors, which grew sharply in the mid-1980s, is
'extremely unlikely'.
Increasing productivity and greater use of technology means that employment
in the insurance and retail banking sectors is likely to undergo further
rationalisation in the short term.
Overall, the financial and business services sectors, which account for
nearly half of Central London's employment, are expected to grow at an
annual rate of between 1.5 per cent and 2 per cent in the next six years.
The bulk of job growth is likely to occur in professional and business
services rather than in the financial sector.
The report's projections are based on the assumption that London retains its
position as Europe's leading financial centre. However, it highlights a
number of potential threats to that position, including inadequate
infrastructure, increased teleworking and competition from other centres
such as Frankfurt.
Mr Peter Damesick, head of research at St Quintin, emphasised the
uncertainties involved in making long-term projections.
'Even the modest increase in occupied floor space in our projections is not
guaranteed,' he said.
The report was commissioned by the Corporation of London, the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors and the Investment Property Forum, a
surveyors' group.
The City of London to the Year 2000 and Beyond: Prospects for Office Demand.
St Quintin Research Department, 33 Cavendish Square, London W1M 9HF. Pounds
20.
</TEXT>
