<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / New town offers Pounds 25m assets sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Irvine Development Corporation yesterday announced that it was putting
its industrial assets up for sale in September at a price of Pounds
20m-Pounds 25m.
The sale of the 1m sq ft of industrial buildings and development land will
be a step towards the winding-up of the Ayrshire new town, which is planned
for the end of 1996.
The corporation's shops and office property portfolio will be put on the
market in the autumn of 1995. The corporation said that this was the biggest
sale of a Scottish new town's industrial assets and the first time a new
town's industrial assets had been offered for purchase by a single buyer.
The industrial portfolio consists of six industrial estates and three groups
of workshops.
So far there have been six sales of industrial estates in Scottish new
towns, which have involved the sale of more than 3.5m sq ft of factories and
development land, raising more than Pounds 50m.
Last October Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, announced that the wind-up
dates of Irvine new town, designated as Scotland's fifth new town in 1966,
had been brought forward by three years.
Livingstone and Cumbernauld new towns are also due to be wound-up in
December 1996. East Kilbride and Glenrothes are scheduled for wind-up by
December 1995.
