<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Peugeot chief warns on sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Calvet, chairman of Peugeot Citroen, the French motor group,
yesterday warned that the French car market was still in a fragile state and
that sales were likely to fall again once the short-term stimulus provided
by the government's incentive scheme wore off. The car market was badly
affected by the recession last year, with the number of new car sales
falling by 18.3 per cent. However a government scheme to offer payments of
FFr5,000 to people trading in vehicles more than 10 years old to buy new
cars helped to fuel a 13.8 per cent sales increase during the first four
months of this year. Yet Mr Calvet said on French radio that the scheme was
likely only to have a short-term effect and that car sales 'may fall or even
return to a relatively weak level' when it ends next year.
