<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Greek rates soar on devaluation fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greek interest rates soared to record levels yesterday amid speculation the
government may be forced to devalue the drachma, following its surprise
decision to free short-term capital movement. To avoid renewed pressure on
the currency, the central bank raised the overnight borrowing rate from 30
to 33 per cent and imposed a surcharge of 0.4 per cent daily - equivalent to
an annual rate of 186 per cent. The three-month interbank lending rate shot
up to 48.5 per cent from 25 per cent on Friday.
The rise in rates seemed to be having the desired effect, with the drachma
closing yesterday at 148.2 against the D-Mark compared to 147.70 on Friday
and at 247.9 against the US dollar compared to 247.1.
Dealers said the surge in interest rates, which saw the one-month interbank
rate touch 70 per cent, reduced pressure on the drachma early in the day and
the central bank was not forced to intervene. Last week, the Bank of Greece
spent some Dollars 1bn of foreign exchange reserves totalling around Dollars
9.5bn to support the currency. However, analysts said pressure would quickly
resume as such high interest rates could not be sustained for long, reviving
fears of a devaluation.
On the other hand, the government would be reluctant to resort to devaluing
the drachma ahead of next month's European parliament elections. A
devaluation would most likely lose the Socialists several percentage points
in their first electoral test since taking office last October.
Instead, the central bank may have to abandon its 'hard drachma' policy,
intended to restrict depreciation this year to around 7 per cent, and let
the currency slide more rapidly.
'We should expect increased depreciation, perhaps an extra 3 and 5 per cent,
over the next couple of weeks,' said Mr Spiros Damaskos of Sigma Money
Brokers.
The government lifted all restrictions on short-term capital movement at the
weekend, six weeks ahead of schedule, in an attempt to ease mounting
pressure on the drachma. Central bank officials said overnight interest
rates (including the surcharge) would go 'into four figures if necessary' in
order to protect the currency.
The Bank of Greece is in the uncomfortable position of having to defend the
drachma on its own, as Greece has never joined the European Union's exchange
rate mechanism, which would allow it to call on other EU central banks for
support.
The government is relying on today's issues of Ecu- and dollar-linked bond
issues at higher interest rates to preventing a heavy outflow of capital and
boost foreign exchange reserves. Dealers said the dollar issue attracted
more than Dollars 100m from institutional investors yesterday, ahead of the
launch.
</TEXT>
