<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Economic Watch: French current account deficit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
France's current account slid to a FFr4.3bn (Pounds 500m) seasonally
adjusted deficit in February from a FFr16.1bn surplus in January, the
economics ministry said yesterday. The ministry said that the deficit
reflected interest coupon payments on French government bonds to
non-residents and an unusually large French contribution to the European
Union that month. The government said that its definitive surplus for 1993
was FFr59.5bn, or 0.5 per cent of gross domestic product, compared with
FFr20.5bn, or 0.3 per cent of GDP, in 1992. France had a basic balance of
payments deficit in February of FFr51.68bn, compared with a deficit of
FFr24.42bn in January and a surplus of FFr13.90bn in February 1993, the
ministry said. The cumulative deficit in the first two months of 1994 was
FFr76.10bn, compared with a surplus of FFr30.65bn in the first two months of
1993.
Italy's public sector deficit narrowed to a provisional L16,100bn (Pounds
6.7bn) in the period January-February 1994 from a L21,410bn deficit in the
corresponding period of 1993, the treasury announced yesterday.
Norway's trade surplus rose to NKr2.86bn (Pounds 264m) in April from
NKr1.67bn in March, the Central Bureau of Statistics said. The cumulative
January-April surplus fell to NKr14.95bn from NKr20.81bn in the same period
a year ago.
Denmark's unemployment in the first quarter of 1994 rose to 13.7 per cent of
the workforce, compared with 13.0 per cent in the first quarter of 1993,
according to the Danish national statistics agency.
</TEXT>
