<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Emerging Markets: Market focus remains on the dollar -
Currency markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign exchanges will again focus on the dollar this week, with markets
anticipating a further tightening of US monetary policy.
The dollar has been fairly stable since central banks intervened to support
it earlier this month, but further stability presumes that the policy-making
Federal Open Markets Committee will lift interest rates when it meets
tomorrow.
The market is expecting a fairly aggressive tightening, with most observers
predicting that the Fed will lift the discount and federal funds rates by 50
basis points. Anything less is likely to lead to a renewed sell-off of the
dollar, and further weakness in the US bond market. The two have traded in
tandem recently.
Last week the dollar gained support from the Bundesbank's aggressive cut of
50 basis points in official interest rates. It also benefited from the Bank
of Japan easing monetary policy, by allowing overnight interest rates to
fall to their lowest level in 18 months.
A tightening from the Fed would represent the final stage in what appears to
have been a concerted sequence of monetary policy initiatives, aimed at
supporting the dollar, after the initial round of intervention.
Mr Steve Hannah, head of research at IBJ International in London, said that
the cut in German rates last week appeared to have given the dollar a solid
base against the D-Mark. He said European investors also tended to believe
that the dollar would recover from current levels.
He is less optimistic, however, about its prospects against the yen.
Although US officials have recently been more emollient in their approach
towards Japan, Mr Hannah doubts whether this will persist if - as he
predicts - the Japanese government fails to deliver on market access
measures.
He said Japanese investors remained sceptical about the outlook for the
dollar. They have a history of poorly performing foreign investments, mostly
because of the strength of the yen. Mr Hannah said he could not foresee
large Japanese capital flows abroad again 'just because the dollar settles
down for a few days.'
In the UK a plethora of economic data, including inflation, unemployment and
retail sales, will be published. The six 'wise men', who offer advice to the
Chancellor on the economy, will deliver their quarterly report, and the
minutes of the April monetary policy meeting will be published.
The data are expected to confirm that the next move in UK rates will be up,
which should support sterling.
</TEXT>
