<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Emerging Markets: News Round-up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TAIWAN
Taiwan has abolished rules restricting foreign insurers from establishing
subsidiaries on the island, agencies report. The finance ministry said that
it had scrapped a rule restricting a foreign insurer from taking a stake of
no more than 30 per cent in a local insurance company. A ceiling of 49 per
cent on total investment by foreigners in a local insurer was also
abolished, the ministry said.
PORTUGAL
The country's bond market is to be reformed next month with a comprehensive
package of measures designed to increase liquidity, improve efficiency and
bring trading practices into line with other European capital markets. The
government has said that the measures will create a wide range of new
instruments.
VENEZUELA
The new tax on private sector debit transactions is not to be applied in
full force to the stock exchange. Instead, the 0.75 per cent tax, taking
effect later this month, will be applied just to the buyer's cheques.
However, Mr Tony Ewell of BZW in London noted that foreign investors would
be taxed another 0.75 per cent when they seek to repatriate their money.
MEXICO
The government has sold the final stake in Telefonos de Mexico, the
telephone utility, in a convertible offering worth up to Dollars 550m. This
concludes the privatisation of Telmex, the largest public company sold by a
developing country. The privatisation began at the end of 1990 when the
government sold a controlling 20.4 per cent stake for Dollars 1.76bn.
CHINA
China plans an increase in B share listings which are denominated in dollars
for foreign investors in an attempt to encourage its stock markets. Mr Liu
Hongru, chairman of the China Securities Regulatory Commission, said the
B-share market was too limited.
Emerging markets coverage appears daily on the World Stock Markets page.
