<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Violence returns to townships: S African leaders compete for
scarce resources ahead of budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN and GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG, CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Africa's respite from its problems ended at the weekend as at least 18
people died in political violence and ministers in the newly formed all-race
government tussled over budget allocations.
The killings and political tensions showed the harsh realities facing the
new government, following the post-election euphoria. President Nelson
Mandela's government also has to make early decisions on economic policy.
Fears of a resurgence of violence grew after 12 bodies were discovered on
Saturday in a house in Thokoza, a black township east of Johannesburg, in
the worst incident since the elections began three weeks ago. Although the
political affiliations of the dead were not immediately known, Thokoza had
been a centre of clashes between supporters of the victorious African
National Congress and the Zulu-dominated Inkatha Freedom party.
A soldier was shot dead in front of a hostel in the township yesterday,
after four gunmen believed to be Inkatha supporters dragged him from a car.
In the KwaZulu/Natal region, where the worst pre-election bloodletting took
place, there were at least five politically motivated deaths over the
weekend. But Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi urged his Inkatha stalwarts to make
peace with their rivals, warning that violence would scare off vital foreign
investment.
Meanwhile, provincial and national leaders have begun competing over scarce
budgetary resources in the run-up to next month's budget.
Mr Ben Turok, a radical political scientist from the University of Durban
Westville, who has called for increased rates and taxes for whites, has been
put in charge of implementing the ANC's reconstruction and development
programme in the Pretoria-Witwatersrand-Vereeniging (PWV) region around
Johannesburg. This is South Africa's economic heartland, responsible for
some 39 per cent of GDP. However, Mr Tokyo Sexwale, the region's premier,
has promised wide consultations before imposing any new measures.
The cabinet will this week begin shaping its legislative agenda, and Mr
Mandela is due to address parliament tomorrow to spell out the government's
plans.
The budget to be presented by Mr Derek Keys, the finance minister, will have
to reconcile many conflicting regional spending needs. The ANC has costed
its reconstruction and development programme at R39bn (Pounds 7.1bn) over
five years. The previous National party government, of which Mr Keys was a
member, said it would cost much more.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
