<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Crest project criticised as 'too complex'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England's handling of the Crest share settlement system has been
sharply criticised by a former executive of the Securities and Investments
Board, the City's chief regulatory watchdog, in an article published late
last week in a legal journal.
The article argues that paperless share settlement, which is due to be in
operation by 1996 or 1997, could have been achieved more cheaply and quickly
by augmenting the stock exchange's existing Talisman and Institutional Net
Settlements systems. It argues that Crest is unnecessarily complex and that
it creates additional risks that do not currently exist in share settlement.
The approach outlined would have left the stock exchange broadly in control
of share settlement and left no visible role for the Bank of England.
It is understood that the article, originally submitted last autumn for
publication in Butterworths Journal of International Banking and Financial
Law, was withdrawn at the request of the Bank of England, which wanted it
delayed at least until after an important Crest taskforce report was
published in February. The author, Ms Kathleen Tyson-Quah, who was an
assistant director in SIB's capital markets division, resigned in March.
The SIB has declined to comment on the article specifically. However, it
said: 'We believe the Crest project is progressing successfully but we don't
wish to make any further comment because we have a formal recognition role
under the Financial Services Act.'
The bank began setting up Crest immediately after the collapse of the stock
exchange's own Taurus project for paperless share trading. The aim in both
cases has been to reduce risk in equities trading by cutting the time
between agreeing a bargain and receiving shares or payment, which requires
the elimination of paper share certificates.
Ms Tyson-Quah argues that instead of building a new system, shares could be
transferred through electronic messages.
Among the great shortcomings of Crest, she argues, is that it calls for
'gross' settlement of equity trades and is likely to require some securities
firms to increase their bank borrowings substantially. Separately, the
British Bankers Association is already holding talks with the Bank of
England about this area.
Responding to the article, the bank said it had considered the option
outlined by Ms Tyson-Quah at an early stage of Crest development but 'all
things considered' decided that Crest was a better option. A key factor was
their view that Talisman is nearly 20 years old and its technology is
insufficiently flexible.
Waves of concern, Page 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
