<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Benny Hill was one of the earliest British casualties of political
correctness. Though his popularity with the general public never waned, he
was banished from British television by the feminists. They sought brownie
points at smart London parties by having fits of the vapours over Hill's
'sexism'. The fact that his comedy was in direct line of descent from
Chaucer and Shakespeare, and that 90 per cent of the audience loved it, was
ignored. Yet ironically he became, simultaneously, a huge success in the US
despite the greater prevalence of feminism there. Benny Hill - Unseen
comprises material produced abroad, late in his life, and not previously
screened here (8.00 ITV). Horizon tells how Barry Marshall happened upon the
real cause of most stomach ulcers but has had an uphill job persuading the
stick-in-the-muds of medicine to abandon their 'stress' diagnosis (8.00
BBC2). The BBC says that today's Panorama will be the one about shenanigans
on Westminster council which was supposed to have been shown just before the
recent local elections (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
