<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Holiday companies escape check-ups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shortage of resources is hampering investigation of holiday companies
accused of providing travellers with inadequate financial protection, says
the body representing trading standards officers.
Mr Alan Street, chief executive of the Institute of Trading Standards
Administration, said in a letter to the Association of Independent Tour
Operators (Aito) last month that the pressure of other work meant officers
had to devote less time to holiday companies.
Under a European Union directive introduced last year, trading standards
officers are responsible for checking that holiday companies have made
arrangements to ensure money can be returned to customers in the case of
corporate collapse.
Mr Street wrote: 'In some areas of the country, the enforcement of the
Package Holiday Directive is not seen as the most pressing of demands and
resources are committed to other matters such as sales of unclassified
videos, unsafe food and consumer products, and attention to the statutory
demands required by more than 50 acts of parliament, together with the
associated 900-plus sets of regulations.'
Aito had written to Mr Street in July last year complaining about 75 tour
operators allegedly operating illegally by not providing proper financial
protection.
Earlier this month, Mr Street again wrote to Aito saying it appeared there
were few operators which did not have adequate financial protection and that
others had stopped selling package holidays.
But he added: 'The greatest difficulty is establishing, without personal
visits, which in themselves are time-consuming and may provoke some
irritation on the part of the recipient operator, what arrangements are in
being.'
