<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Pensions provision poses hard choices for the future:
Targeted state schemes and new company plans urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Personal pensions have had a bad press in the past year. Yet the controversy
over how they have been sold has obscured a larger issue: whether the rise
of personal pensions is a passing fashion or a permanent change in pensions
provision.
In the past few years, the structure of pension provision in the UK has been
revolutionised and with it the relative incomes of pensioners.
The revolution, the details of which are outlined in Pension Policy in the
UK: an Economic Analysis, published today by the Institute for Fiscal
Studies, means pensioners are no longer society's poorest group.
The income of richer pensioners has risen faster than average incomes over
the past 15 years or so: for the top 20 per cent of pensioners the rise was
more than 50 per cent between 1979 and 1990-91. But the gulf between rich
and poor pensioners widened.
In the same period, incomes of the poorest 20 per cent rose by only about 10
per cent.
State benefits now make up only half of pensioner incomes. For those reliant
largely on state-provided pensions the future does not look rosy: the value
of the contributory basic pension fell from 20 per cent of average male
earnings at the end of the 1970s to 15 per cent at the start of the 1990s.
By the middle of the next century it will fall to just 6 per cent or 7 per
cent. The generosity of the supplementary State Earnings Related Pension
Scheme (Serps) was curtailed in the 1980s.
Increasingly, the income-tested sector (income support and housing related
benefits) will be a significant source of income for the poorest elderly
people while the rest come to rely more on private income.
The perception that state provision is diminishing has fuelled the expansion
of the personal pension sector. This growth in individual provision has been
enhanced partly because coverage of workers by traditional occupational
pension schemes peaked over two decades ago. In future, more people will
retire with pension values determined by the success of their plan's
investments rather than the scheme's tenure or earnings.
The extent of these shifts is often underestimated. For example, among
private-sector workers covered by a private pension, a majority (about 6m)
belong to a contracted out money purchase or personal pension rather than to
an occupational scheme (5.6m), according to the government actuary.
Should this trend towards personal provision be resisted?
As far as the basic pension is concerned a coherent and transparent policy
is needed which will continue the move towards greater targeting of state
resources, without creating the pitfalls of the current system of
means-testing.
Given the increasing diversity of pensioner incomes and the future increase
in the numbers of pensioners simply raising benefit levels within the
present structure will be expensive and inappropriate.
It is often suggested that personal pensions are inherently riskier than
other forms of provision. But reliance on state pensions is also risky:
policy changes over the past 15 years have reduced both basic and earnings
related components below expectations.
The move towards defined contribution schemes feeds on some of the risks
attached to traditional defined benefit schemes.
Such schemes are inappropriate for many. Traditional occupational schemes
penalise those who move jobs frequently, and often reward long servers and
high earners disproportionately. So long as they do, defined contribution
schemes, which are more flexible, will spread. In the US since 1975, 80 per
cent of newly covered workers have joined defined contribution schemes. To
compete, traditional occupational schemes must reform.
This article has been contributed by Richard Disney, Paul Johnson and Edward
Whitehouse, the book's authors, who are with the Institute for Fiscal
Studies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
