<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Insurance sales manager sacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
General Portfolio, the insurance company, sacked one of its sales managers
on Friday for a serious breach of training practices.
The company, which has 67 branches in the UK and contracts with 1,600 sales
agents, has also suspended two other managers in its direct-sales branch at
Farnborough, Hampshire, while it considers their 'suitability to carry out
their responsibilities'. The sacking offence occurred towards the end of
last year.
These actions follow an investigation into allegations that managers at the
branch did not follow training procedures for new sales agents.
The manager was fired for falsifying sales-agent training records. Lautro,
the life industry's self-regulating body, stipulates that managers must keep
records of observations made during meetings between new sales agents and
potential clients.
The company specifies that managers must keep records of four such meetings.
The company found that one manager had completed records 'confirming his
presence at a meeting between a company representative and the client
despite not being present'.
Former sales agents also alleged that managers encouraged them to use
unauthorised competition entry forms offering potential customers prizes to
tempt them to buying products.
The company's investigation comes in the midst of controversy surrounding
the sale of personal-investment products, particularly pensions. In recent
months Lautro has fined several companies for breaching industry standards.
Mr Paul Smith and Mr Richard Hannan, two former sales agents, also alleged
that before a compliance office visit in December, a memo was sent out
ordering consultants to destroy all 'unauthorised' competition entry forms.
They also said they were only aware of one of the advertised prize draws
taking place.
General Portfolio said its head office had approved three of the competition
entry forms and that the remaining unauthorised forms were destroyed on the
request of the company's compliance office.
The company said it had no evidence that breaches in the Farnborough branch
were 'anything other than an isolated incident'.
