<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Graduate pay faces squeeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Expansion of higher education in the UK could force employers to change
their recruitment strategies and reduce starting salaries, says a report
published by the Institute of Manpower Studies today.
Evidence from the US, where the number of university degrees awarded doubled
between 1962 and 1972, and then continued to increase at a much slower rate,
shows that real graduate starting salaries have fallen since 1969.
In the UK, student numbers in higher education have increased by more than
50 per cent during the past five years, and similar trends are expected to
develop.
According to the IMS research, real US starting salaries peaked at Dollars
25,288 (at 1990 values) in 1969, and fell 16 per cent by 1990 to Dollars
21,319.
The number of graduates failing to use their degree, or 'under-utilised',
increased during the same period from 11 per cent to 20 per cent, and this
proportion is projected to increase to 30 per cent by the year 2005. Such
graduates ended up in jobs including retail sales, clerical work, and craft
and labourer occupations not traditionally regarded as needing a degree.
IMS also found profound changes in the way graduates looked for work, with
students needing to be far more 'proactive' in looking for work.
The US Labour Market for New Graduates, IMS Report 267, BEBC, PO Box 1496,
Parkstone, Poole, Dorset, BH12 3YD. Pounds 40.
</TEXT>
