<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Quality of life 'barely above 1950'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quality of life in Britain is worse than in the mid-1970s and hardly higher
than in 1950 when some goods were still rationed, says a report published
today.
Researchers from the Stockholm Environment Institute use consumer
expenditure as the base measure for a quality of life index and adjust it by
20 factors ranging from conventional measures, such as net capital growth,
to factors such as the costs of commuting and of lost farmland.
The index aims to replace gross national product as a broader measure of
affluence.
The researchers say that 'sustainable economic welfare is not the same as
GNP, and has departed from it from the mid-1970s onwards'.
Their calculations suggest that, between 1950 and 1990, GNP per head grew by
230 per cent in real terms, or an average of 2.1 per cent per year. The
researchers' index grew by just 3 per cent over the entire period.
Since the 1970s the researchers' index has been falling at an average rate
of almost 5 per cent a year. Much of the decline is accounted for by the
fall in value of natural assets such as North Sea oil.
In the case of measuring the cost of lost farmland, the researchers subtract
a value of the land lost to urbanisation and the fall in farming
productivity as the soil quality deteriorates.
But even without accounting for the depletion of natural resources, the
index is still at the level of the early 1970s, having almost doubled
between 1950 and 1970.
The researchers blame increasing inequality in the distribution of incomes.
They say an income increase of Pounds 1,000 a year for a poor family means a
much sharper improvement in quality of life than the same gain would for a
rich one. This phenomenon is seen when the method is applied to the US, but
the divergence is more marked in the UK.
Measuring Sustainable Economic Welfare - A Pilot Index 1950-1990. Stockholm
Environment Institute. Box 2142, S-103 14 Stockholm, Sweden. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
    P9641 Regulation of Agricultural Marketing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
