<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Tories remove Smith references from manifesto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative party officials announced yesterday that references to John
Smith in the party's European election manifesto were being deleted before
its delayed launch next week.
That followed Friday's postponement by the government of the white paper on
competitiveness, a gesture intended to underpin the new, less
confrontational mood of British politics ushered in by Mr Smith's death.
But a row over campaign literature prepared by the Tories before Mr Smith's
death last week underlined the fragility of the present suspension of
hostilities between the main parties.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader and a long-time campaigner
against personal mudslinging at Westminster, said he was worried that the
new mood would not last.
Close colleagues of Mr Major, who like Mr Smith has a reputation for
integrity, said the prime minister saw a genuine opportunity for politicians
on all sides to raise the level of political debate. In the process they
could seek to rebuild their battered reputations with voters.
But the dispute over the alleged 'smears' in the latest edition of the
Conservatives' campaign guide was seen by many at Westminster as a more
reliable pointer to the future.
The guide included many familiar attacks on Mr Smith's leadership,
describing him as 'ineffectual' and 'visionless'. Its tone contrasted
sharply with the fulsome tribute to the former Labour leader by Mr Major in
the Commons on Thursday.
Ministers insisted the criticisms were simply part of the normal
'rough-and-tumble' of politics during elections campaigns and pointed to
similar personal attacks by Labour figures on Mr Major's leadership.
But Mr David Blunkett, the Labour party chairman, said the guide advised
Tory candidates in the forthcoming European elections to say 'very personal
and unpleasant things which had little to do with the policy differences we
have in Europe'.
He added: 'This personal abuse contrasts with what has happened over the
last three days.'
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, had planned to
launch the white paper on British competitiveness alongside Mr Major and
several other cabinet ministers later today. However officials said it would
be delayed at least until next week.
Bookmakers William Hill made Mr Tony Blair the favourite for the Labour
leadership. He was originally quoted at 2-5 and is now 1-5, with others as
follows: Gordon Brown 4-1, Robin Cook 8-1, John Prescott 12-1, Margaret
Beckett 20-1, Jack Cunningham 33-1.
Labour are 8-11 favourites to win the next general election, with the
Conservatives at even money.
</TEXT>
