<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Union stands aside from Labour race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Jinkinson, general secretary of Unison, the public services union,
yesterday said that the union executive would make no recommendation on the
new leader of the Labour party to those members who pay the political levy.
Unison's stance, announced at the start of its annual conference, was not
unexpected since only parts of the union are affiliated to the Labour party,
but some other union leaders may follow the lead.
Some leaders said at the weekend that they hoped the new party leader would
emerge without a contest, as they honoured the request not to name their
preferences at least until after the funeral of John Smith later this week.
But yesterday Mr Bill Jordan, the AEEU engineering union president, said:
'It would please us no end if a natural leader emerged. If the politicians
within the Labour party believe they have consensus among themselves on who
should be their natural leader I'm fairly certain that would be welcomed
throughout the trade union movement.'
The AEEU would probably back either Mr Tony Blair or Mr Gordon Brown in the
event of a contest.
Most unions, including the TGWU general union, Labour's biggest affiliate,
are expected to hold postal ballots but some may opt for cheaper workplace
ballots. 'We certainly hope that everyone will go for postal ballots; we all
know that workplace ballots are not always transparently fair in all
workplaces,' said one union leader.
Unison and other large unions confirmed yesterday that a July election was
perfectly practical, although some smaller unions might have an
organisational problem. The election will be open to some abuse as the
electorate should not only be political-levy payers but also supporters of
the Labour party, something which will be difficult in practice to
ascertain.
Assuming that most unions do make recommendations, the field looks wide
open. Leaders have been stunned by Mr Smith's death and have been careful
not to repeat the 'undignified rush' to publicly anoint his successor as
happened in Mr Smith's favour after Mr Neil Kinnock's resignation.
One official said last night that 'the heart is for Prescott but the head is
for Blair or Brown'. Another added: 'Union leaders are just desperate to win
and there is a grudging acceptance in some quarters that Blair is the only
one who can do it.'
Separately at the Unison conference, Mr Jinkinson yesterday committed the
union to a protracted campaign against the public-sector pay-bill freeze and
job cutting programme. He urged members however not to be drawn into early
industrial action.
</TEXT>
