<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Doctors resolve dispute with OFT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A dispute that threatened to lead to legal action by the British Medical
Association against the Office of Fair Trading has been resolved.
In February the Monopolies and Mergers Commission recommended that the BMA
should stop publishing fee guidelines for private practice by consultants.
The government accepted the recommendation, saying the commission had
established that doctors following the recommended scales could charge
higher fees than would otherwise be possible, and the BMA immediately agreed
to stop publishing and distributing the guidelines.
Since February, however, a disagreement has raged between the BMA and OFT
over the form in which its undertaking to stop publishing the guidelines
should be formally expressed.
The BMA complained that a form of words demanded by the OFT went beyond the
scope of the original commission recommendation on private medical services,
and could have been interpreted to cover guidance on such activities as
certificates written by general practitioners and medical examinations for
legal actions.
After taking counsel's opinion, BMA officials told the OFT that, unless the
matter was resolved satisfactorily by the end of last week, they would seek
judicial review. The BMA said yesterday that a satisfactory form of words
had now been accepted by both sides.
Although the BMA agreed to withdraw its guidelines after the government
accepted the commission report, it has made clear that it regards the entire
issue as perverse. Private medical insurers such as Bupa and PPP will be
free to continue issuing guidelines.
</TEXT>
